    "title": "Hourglass",
    "description": "[pose the problem as being about the world, not the study of the world]\n\n“There is no better high than discovery.”\n― Edward O. Wilson\n\n“You can't study the darkness by flooding it with light.”\n― Edward Abbey\n\n“Listen, O lord of the meeting rivers,\nthings standing shall fall,\nbut the moving ever shall stay.”\n― Basava\n\n&quot;Criticism is only of value in so far as it trains your observation so that it can eventually be turned on yourself. That is the purpose of criticism. I used to criticize everyone and everything; but afterwards I turned that criticism upon myself to see if that which I criticized outside myself remained in my own heart and mind. The moment I turned that light of criticism upon myself, I began to grow, I began to destroy the unessential.&quot;\n- Jiddu Krishnamurti, 'Early Works', circa 1930",
